Xchange Transactions Forecast




Intro

Xchange is a foreign currency exchange business interested in forecasting the number of transactions they are going to have based on historical transaction data. They operate in Canada, New Zealand and Portugal, and they are particularly interested in forecasting Portugal’s transactions.

The data is a simple hourly transactions table by country:

hourly_transactions <- read_csv("hourly_transactions.csv") %>% 
  left_join(read_csv("country_table.csv")) %>% 
  select(-country_id) %>% 
  mutate(
    datetime = dmy_hm(datetime)
  )

Time Series Model

Xchange is interested only in assessing whether is it possible to forecast accurately one day’s worth of data rather than putting the model in production. Hence to build the model the data was split into training and test sets rather than adopting a slide-validation approach which would be an overkill for the task.

Training data comprises data from 01/01/2019 until the 30/07/2020. The 31st of July 2020 was kept as a test set. A slide-validation architecture would repeat this any number of times by sliding the training/test divide increasing the date on which the cutoff is performed and adding each iteration the prediction as a new observation to the training set. For this study, as explained, a single modeling round is done for Portugal only.

A 2-layer, 128 units each, bidirectional LSTM (long-short term memory) neural network was built to model the data. The independent variable was a lag 1 hourly transactions and the dependent variable simply hourly_transactions. This creates the sequence necessary to model a time series being the previous value of hourly transactions the predictor for the next one. Early stopping was implemented so the model would stop training once the mean squared error of the prediction on the training set didn’t decrease and a measure to decrease the learning rate on plateauing was implemented in order to reach a global or an acceptable local training loss minima.


import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
  
hourly_transactions = pd.read_csv("hourly_transactions.csv").merge(pd.read_csv("country_table.csv")).drop("country_id", axis=1)
hourly_transactions = hourly_transactions.loc[hourly_transactions["country_name"] == "Portugal",:]

data = hourly_transactions.loc[:, "datetime":"transactions"]
train, test = data.loc[data["datetime"] < "31/07/2020",:], data.loc[data["datetime"] >= "31/07/2020",:]
xtrain, xtest = train["transactions"].to_numpy(), test["transactions"].to_numpy()
ytrain, ytest = train["transactions"].shift(periods= -1, fill_value=0).to_numpy(), test["transactions"].shift(periods= -1, fill_value=0).to_numpy()
xtrain, xtest = np.reshape(xtrain, (xtrain.shape[0],1,1)), np.reshape(xtest, (xtest.shape[0],1,1))

# define and compile model
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(128, return_sequences=True), input_shape=(None, xtrain.shape[2])),
        tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(128)),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1)])

my_callbacks = [tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='loss', patience=5, verbose=1), 
                tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor="loss", patience=10,verbose=1, restore_best_weights=True)]
    
model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer="Adam", metrics=["mae"])

# fit model
history = model.fit(x=xtrain, 
          y=ytrain,
          validation_data = (xtest,ytest),
          epochs=1000, 
          verbose=1, 
          batch_size=100, 
          callbacks=[my_callbacks])

The model trained for ~ 250 epochs reaching a mean average error of ~ 280 hourly transactions on the validation set. The training and validation MSE and MAE fall as the model continued to train:

# model build assessment
mae = history.history['mae']
val_mae = history.history['val_mae']
loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
epochs = range(len(mae))

plt.plot(epochs, mae, 'g', label='Training mae')
plt.plot(epochs, val_mae, 'b', label='Validation mae')
plt.title('Training and validation mae')
plt.legend(loc=0)
plt.draw()
fig1 = plt.gcf()
fig1.savefig('mae.png',dpi=100)
plt.show()

plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'g', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.legend(loc=0)
plt.draw()
fig2 = plt.gcf()
fig2.savefig('loss.png',dpi=100)
plt.show()

# model performance on test set (31st of July)

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error

test_pred = pd.DataFrame()
test_pred["y"] = ytest
test_pred["y_hat"] = model.predict(xtest)
test_MAE = mean_absolute_error(test_pred["y"],test_pred["y_hat"])
test_RMSE = mean_squared_error(test_pred["y"],test_pred["y_hat"], squared=False)
print("Mean Absolute Error of " + str(test_MAE) + " on the overall transactions prediction for 31st of July 2020")
## Mean Absolute Error of 285.84585698445636 on the overall transactions prediction for 31st of July 2020
print("Root Mean Squared Error of " + str(test_RMSE) + " on the overall transactions prediction for 31st of July 2020")
## Root Mean Squared Error of 427.8819538722636 on the overall transactions prediction for 31st of July 2020

To give a better intuition on whether this is an acceptable model performance we can visualise predictions overlaying observed and predicted hourly transactions on the training as well as the test data. We create the following prediction tables first:

#train
train_observed = pd.DataFrame()
train_observed["date"] = train["datetime"]
train_observed["transactions"] = np.reshape(xtrain, (xtrain.shape[0],1))
train_predicted = pd.DataFrame()
train_predicted["date"] = train["datetime"].shift(periods= -1, fill_value=0)
train_predicted["predicted_transactions"] = model.predict(xtrain)
train_preds = train_observed.join(train_predicted, lsuffix='_obs', rsuffix='_pred')
print(train_preds.head())

Then we visualise the results aggregated by daily transactions on the training set from 01/01/2020 and hourly transactions on 31/07/2020, that is the test set. The blue are the observed and green the predicted transactions.

We get from these plots the intuition of the model doing a rather good job at forecasting transactions, facing perhaps more problems at forecasting accurately the times were transactions peak unprecedentedly. Arguably more such occurrences are needed in order for the model to learn them and do a better job at predicting them. Nevertheless it may be argued the time series does a satisfactory job at forecasting hourly transactions.
